      <h1>Privacy Policy for BetLord</h1>
      <div class="meta">Effective Date: May 1, 2026</div>

      <p>BetLord ("the Bot") is operated by Oxidant Corporation and developed by Chisom Epoch. This Privacy Policy outlines how information is collected, used, and protected when you interact with the Bot via Telegram.</p>

      <h2>1. Information Collected</h2>
      <p>The Bot may collect and process the following:</p>
      <p>- Telegram account details (user ID, username, profile metadata)</p>
      <p>- Messages, commands, and interactions with the Bot</p>
      <p>- Technical and usage data (timestamps, activity patterns, preferences)</p>

      <h2>2. Purpose of Data Use</h2>
      <p>Collected information is used strictly to:</p>
      <p>- Provide core functionality, including delivery of betting insights and signals</p>
      <p>- Enhance system performance, accuracy, and user experience</p>
      <p>- Maintain system integrity, detect abuse, and ensure proper operation</p>

      <h2>3. Data Sharing and Disclosure</h2>
      <p>User data is not sold, traded, or commercially distributed. Limited disclosure may occur only where necessary to:</p>
      <p>- Support essential infrastructure (e.g., secure hosting, analytics services)</p>
      <p>- Comply with legal obligations or valid regulatory requests</p>

      <h2>4. Data Retention</h2>
      <p>Information is retained only for as long as required to fulfill operational purposes or comply with applicable obligations. Data no longer required is securely discarded.</p>

      <h2>5. Security Measures</h2>
      <p>Appropriate administrative and technical safeguards are implemented to protect data against unauthorized access, alteration, or misuse. However, no digital system guarantees absolute security.</p>

      <h2>6. User Control and Rights</h2>
      <p>You may discontinue use of the Bot at any time. Requests regarding data access or deletion can be made via the contact provided below.</p>

      <h2>7. External Dependencies</h2>
      <p>The Bot may rely on third-party data providers (e.g., odds and market feeds). Their independent policies govern how they handle data.</p>

